href=\"/wiki/Bayou_St._John\" title=\"Bayou St. John\">Bayou St. John</a> for \"Super Sunday\" 1991</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Mardi Gras Indians</b> (also known as Black Masking Indians) are black <a href=\"/wiki/Carnival\" title=\"Carnival\">carnival</a> revelers in <a href=\"/wiki/New_Orleans,_Louisiana\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"New Orleans, Louisiana\">New Orleans, Louisiana</a>, who dress up for <a href=\"/wiki/Mardi_Gras_in_New_Orleans\" title=\"Mardi Gras in New Orleans\">Mardi Gras</a> in suits influenced by <a href=\"/wiki/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States\" title=\"Native Americans in the United States\">Native American</a> ceremonial apparel.\n</p><p>Collectively, their organizations are called \"tribes\". There are about 38 tribes which range in size from half a dozen to several dozen members. The groups are largely independent, but a pair of umbrella organizations loosely coordinates the Uptown Indians and the Downtown Indians.\n</p><p>In addition to Mardi Gras Day, many of the tribes also parade on Saint Joseph's Day (March 19) and the Sunday nearest to Saint Joseph's Day (\"Super Sunday\"). Traditionally, these were the only times Mardi Gras Indians were seen in public in full regalia. The <a href=\"/wiki/New_Orleans_Jazz_%26_Heritage_Festival\" title=\"New Orleans Jazz &amp; Heritage Festival\">New Orleans Jazz &amp; Heritage Festival</a> began the practice of hiring tribes to appear at the Festival as well. In recent years it has become more common to see Mardi Gras Indians at other festivals and parades in the city.\n</p><p>Notwithstanding the popularity of such activities for tourists and residents alike, the phenomenon of the Mardi Gras Indians is said to reflect both a vital musical history and an equally vital attempt to express internal social dynamics.<sup id=\"cite_ref-draper_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-draper-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\" role=\"navigation\" aria-labelledby=\"mw-toc-heading\"><input type=\"checkbox\" mid-19th century, possibly before. The history of the Mardi Gras Indians is shrouded in mystery and folklore.\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Congo_Square\">Congo Square</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mardi_Gras_Indians&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Congo Square\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Indian30.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Indian30.jpg/220px-Indian30.jpg\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"220\" height=\"288\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Indian30.jpg/330px-Indian30.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/52/Indian30.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"424\" data-file-height=\"555\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Indian30.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Mardi Gras Indian getting ready</div></div></div>\n<p>In 1740, New Orleans' <a href=\"/wiki/Congo_Square\" title=\"Congo Square\">Congo Square</a> was a cultural center for African music and dance.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  New Orleans was more liberal than many Southern cities, and on Sundays African slaves gathered to sing folk songs, play traditional music, and dance.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The lively parties were recounted by a Northern observer as being \"indescribable... Never will you see gayer countenances, demonstrations of more forgetfulness of the past and the future, and more entire abandonment to the joyous existence to the present movement.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  The idea of letting loose and embracing traditional African music and dance is a backbone of the Mardi Gras Indians practice.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Native_American_and_African_American_encounters\">Native American and African American encounters</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mardi_Gras_Indians&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Native American and African American encounters\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>As a major southern trade port, <a href=\"/wiki/New_Orleans\" title=\"New Orleans\">New Orleans</a> became a cultural melting pot.\n</p><p>During the late 1740s and 1750s, many enslaved Africans fled to the <a href=\"/wiki/Bayous\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bayous\">bayous</a> of Louisiana where they encountered Native Americans.  Years later, after the Civil War, hundreds of freed slaves joined the U.S. Ninth Cavalry Regiment, also known as <a href=\"/wiki/Buffalo_Soldiers\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buffalo Soldiers\">Buffalo Soldiers</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The Buffalo Soldiers fought, killed, forced, and aided the mass removal and relocation of the <a href=\"/wiki/Plains_Indians\" title=\"Plains Indians\">Plains Indians</a> on the Western Frontier.  After returning to New Orleans, many ex-soldiers joined popular Wild West shows, most notably <a href=\"/wiki/Buffalo_Bill%27s_Wild_West\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buffalo Bill&#39;s Wild West\">Buffalo Bill's Wild West</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The show wintered in New Orleans from 1884 to 1885 and was hailed by the <i><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Daily_Picayune&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Daily Picayune (page does not exist)\">Daily Picayune</a></i> as \"the people's choice\". There was at least one black cowboy in the show, and there were numerous black cowhands.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On Mardi Gras in 1885, 50 to 60 Plains Indians marched in native dress on the streets of New Orleans.  Later that year, the first Mardi Gras Indian gang was formed; the tribe was named \"The Creole Wild West\" and was most likely composed of members of Buffalo Bill's Wild West show,<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> although the \"Indian gangs\" might predate their appearance in the parades.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Suits\">Suits</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mardi_Gras_Indians&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Suits\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Mardi Gras Indian suits cost thousands of dollars in materials alone and can weigh upwards of one hundred pounds.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  A suit usually takes between six and nine months to plan and complete.  Each Indian designs and creates his own suit; elaborate bead patches depict meaningful and symbolic scenes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  Beads, feathers, and sequins are integral parts of a Mardi Gras Indian suit.  Uptown New Orleans tribes tend to have more sculptural and abstract African-inspired suits; downtown tribes have more pictorial suits with heavy Native American influences.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Moser_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Moser-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Parade_formation_and_protocol\">Parade formation and protocol</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mardi_Gras_Indians&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Parade formation and protocol\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:MardiGrasIndians.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/MardiGrasIndians.jpg/220px-MardiGrasIndians.jpg\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"220\" height=\"132\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/MardiGrasIndians.jpg/330px-MardiGrasIndians.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/MardiGrasIndians.jpg/440px-MardiGrasIndians.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3264\" data-file-height=\"1952\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:MardiGrasIndians.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Uptown Mardi Gras Indians Encounter on Mardi Gras Day</div></div></div>\n<p>The Mardi Gras Indians play various traditional roles.  Many blocks ahead of the Indians are plain clothed informants keeping an eye out for any danger.  The procession begins with \"spyboys,\" dressed in light \"running suits\" that allow them the freedom to move quickly in case of emergency.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Next comes the \"first flag,\" an ornately dressed Indian carrying a token tribe flag.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Closest to the \"Big Chief\" is the \"Wildman\" who usually carries a symbolic weapon.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Finally, there is the \"Big Chief.\"  The \"Big Chief\" decides where to go and which tribes to meet (or ignore).  The entire group is followed by percussionists and revelers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-SmithGovenar_2-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-SmithGovenar-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>During the march, the Indians dance and sing traditional songs particular to their gang.  They use hodgepodge languages loosely based on different African dialects.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The \"Big Chief\" decides where the group will parade; the parade route is different each time.  When two tribes come across each other, they either pass by or meet for a symbolic fight.  Each tribe lines up and the \"Big Chiefs\" taunt each other about their suits and their tribes.  The drum beats of the two tribes intertwine, and the face off is complete.  Both tribes continue on their way.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Violence\">Violence</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mardi_Gras_Indians&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: Violence\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In the early days of the Indians, Mardi Gras was a day of both reveling and bloodshed.   \"Masking\" and parading was a time to settle grudges.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003_4-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> This part of Mardi Gras Indian history is immortalized in James Sugar Boy Crawford's song, \"Jock O Mo\" (better known and often covered as \"<a href=\"/wiki/Iko_Iko\" title=\"Iko Iko\">Iko Iko</a>\"), based on their taunting chants. However, in the late 1960s, <a href=\"/wiki/Allison_Montana\" title=\"Allison Montana\">Allison Montana</a>, \"Chief of Chiefs\", fought to end violence between the Mardi Gras Indian Tribes.<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> He said, \"I was going to make them stop fighting with the gun and the knife and start fighting with the needle and thread.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Today, the Mardi Gras Indians are not plagued by violence; instead, they base their fights over the \"prettiness\" of their suits.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003_4-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Gaudet,_Marcia_2003-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span
